summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Community and Peer Mentorship as Anchors
summaries.summaryText: Peer mentors and cultural centers helped Luis navigate isolation as a first-gen Latino student. [Part 3/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 1]
Served as a teaching assistant for an introductory design course, emphasizing peer inclusivity. [Timeline 3]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 2]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 3]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 1]
Presented a project on sustainable energy systems at an undergraduate research showcase. [Timeline 3]

Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 2]
Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 2]

themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: At first I thought I wasn’t smart enough, but then I realized everyone’s struggling; we just don’t talk about it. [Context 3]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Aaliyah reflecting on the impact of representation and visibility.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 4]
